      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Case of Wen Ho Lee: The Questions Linger</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Harvard Hollenberg letter criticizes Times 'apologia, of sorts' regarding coverage of Wen Ho Lee case involving nuclear secrets taken from Los Alamos National Laboratory</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Times and Wen Ho Lee'' (Note ''From the Editors,'' Sept. 26):</p>
        <p>Your apologia, of sorts, regarding your coverage of the dubious case of Wen Ho Lee suggests a false premise: that the presumption of innocence applies only in the courtroom and need create no barrier to the coverage of alleged crimes.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Times and Wen Ho Lee'' (Note ''From the Editors,'' Sept. 26):</p>
        <p>Your apologia, of sorts, regarding your coverage of the dubious case of Wen Ho Lee suggests a false premise: that the presumption of innocence applies only in the courtroom and need create no barrier to the coverage of alleged crimes.</p>
        <p>You seem to evade the question of whether your civic duty to inform readers of continuing criminal investigations creates an inherent conflict of interest with what I hope you have now learned is your corresponding duty not to implicate individuals in ''infamous crimes,'' as characterized by the Fifth Amendment, even before they are indicted, let alone convicted.</p>
        <p>HARVARD HOLLENBERG  New York, Sept. 26, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a lawyer.</p>
      </block>
